[According to OIE's Aquatic Manual, spring viremia of carp (SVC) is a rhabdovirus infection capable of inducing an acute haemorrhagic and contagious viremia in several carp species and of some other cyprinid and ictalurid fish species.

For the above and additional background information, including diagnostic methods and references, please refer to chapter 2.3.8 Spring Viremia of Carp at http://www.oie.int/fileadmin/Home/eng/Health_standards/aahm/current/2.3.08_SVC.pdf.

The following information was obtained from the Fish Health Inspectorate (FHI), Centre for Environment, Fisheries and Aquaculture Science (CEFAS), Fact Sheet on Spring Viraemia of Carp http://www.defra.gov.uk/aahm/files/Guide-SVC.pdf.

"Clinical signs vary but can include darkening of the skin, swollen eyes, abdominal swelling (dropsy), pale gills, trailing fecal casts, and protrusion of the anus. Infected fish may be lethargic, show loss of balance, and display areas of bleeding on the gills, skin, and internal organs. It is important to note that one or more of these signs may be absent at any stage of the outbreak, especially during the earliest and very late stages. SVC is usually spread through close contact between infected fish.

There is no firm evidence to suggest that the disease can be transmitted vertically through the egg. Some vectors such as the fish louse _Argulus_ spp and the fish leech _Piscicola geometra_ can also transfer the disease from diseased to healthy fish.

There is no known treatment for SVC.

As a notifiable disease in the UK, there is a legal obligation to report any suspicion of a clinical outbreak of SVC to the Fish Health Inspectorate (FHI)".

For details of how SVC is diagnosed and controlled, download CEFAS guidance on notifiable diseases in fish from the aquatic animal health movements website (Pages 15 and 16) at http://www.defra.gov.uk/aahm/files/leaflet-notifiable-diseases.pdf.

There is no indication that SVC is a threat to human health (http://www.cfsph.iastate.edu/Factsheets/pdfs/spring_viremia_of_carp.pdf).

Photos on post-mortem lesions can be seen at http://library.enaca.org/Health/FieldGuide/html/svc1.htm and http://www.dnr.state.mn.us/fish_diseases/svc.html.

In relation to the epidemiological comments re the batch imported 8 Apr 2014: Hong-Kong indicated, in the most recent periodic OIE report, SVC as a disease "never reported" in the country. See the last 6-monthly report (July to December 2013) at http://www.oie.int/wahis_2/public/wahid.php/Reviewreport/semestrial/review?year=2013&semester=2&wild=0&country=HKG&this_country_code=HKG&detailed=1. - Mod CRD

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail map can be accessed at: https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=2453455,4229.]
